Simulation with model selection by BIC

Simulation set up

  • Sample size for both training and testing set is 200
  • 50 covariates, 10 groups, 5 covariates each group
  • group 1 and 3 are important, with beta = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
  • signal-to-noise ratio = 1
  • use BIC to select lambda
  • use prediction error to evaluate prediction
  • tuning parameter of weight: 0, .25, .5, .75, 1, no scale

zero correlation for both inter and intra group

load("../Data/sim_bic_no_cor.RData")
pe_df1 <- pe_df1 %>% melt()
## No id variables; using all as measure variables
cpp_df1 <- cpp_df1 %>% melt()
## No id variables; using all as measure variables

All iterations

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
boxplot(value ~ variable, data = pe_df1, ylab = "prediction error", names = c("Lasso", "GL", "CGL", "rCGL"))
boxplot(value ~ variable, data = cpp_df1, ylab = "Cost per prediction", names = c("Lasso", "GL", "CGL", "rCGL"))

pe_df1 %>% group_by(variable) %>% summarise(ave_pe = mean(value),
                                            med_pe = median(value)) 
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   variable        ave_pe med_pe
##   <fct>            <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 lasso             1.22   1.21
## 2 grp_lasso         1.13   1.12
## 3 cost_grep_lasso   1.14   1.13
## 4 wcost_grp_lasso   1.13   1.12
cpp_df1 %>% group_by(variable) %>% summarise(ave_cpp = mean(value),
                                             med_cpp = median(value))
